Duck typing, on the other hand, is a concept in object-oriented programming that allows an object to be treated as if it were a different type of object, as long as it has the same methods and properties as the original type. This means that if an object has the methods and properties that are expected of a particular type, it can be treated as if it were that type, even if it doesn't inherit from that type or have the same class.

In TypeScript, duck typing is used to enable developers to use objects of different types interchangeably, as long as they have the same methods and properties. For example, if you have an object that has a `sayHello()` method, you can use it with any type of object that also has that method, regardless of their class or inheritance.

Here's an example of how duck typing works in TypeScript:
```
interface Animal {
  sayHello(): void;
}

class Dog implements Animal {
  sayHello(): void {
    console.log("Woof!");
  }
}

class Cat implements Animal {
  sayHello(): void {
    console.log("Meow!");
  }
}

const animal = {
  sayHello(): void {
    console.log("Bark!");
  }
};

// Animal is a duck-typed interface, so we can use any object that has the sayHello method
animal as any = new Dog(); // okay
animal as any = new Cat(); // okay
animal as any = { sayHello(): void { console.log("Meow!"); } }; // okay
```
In this example, the `Animal` interface defines a `sayHello()` method, and the `Dog` and `Cat` classes implement this interface. However, the `animal` variable can be assigned any object that has the `sayHello()` method, regardless of its class or inheritance. This is because `animal` is duck-typed, meaning it can be treated as if it were any type of object that has the same methods and properties.

Overall, duck typing in TypeScript allows developers to write more flexible and modular code, while still benefiting from the type safety and error checking provided by TypeScript.

